article.headline: 12-4 second-half run helps Sun pull away
article.linkText: Sales, Whalen lead Sun past Sting
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut Sun coach Mike Thibault
kept his cool during Charlotte's fast start. That was all his
players needed to see.

Nykesha Sales went on to score 20 points and Lindsay Whalen
added a career-high 11 and the Sun rallied for a 71-62 victory
Thursday night over the Sting.

"We saw the confidence in coach, the Don't worry about it, the
shots will come," Sales said. "We didn't see any fright in his
face and we sort of responded to that."

They responded with defense, pressing and disrupting Charlotte's
deliberate pace, deflecting shots and combining for 11 steals.
Whalen, a rookie guard, had a career-high four steals and five
assists for Connecticut (2-2), which started the season with
consecutive losses. The Sun got 26 points off 18 turnovers.

"Defense is a priority," Sales said. "In order to win, every
team has to have it."

Kelly Mazzante had a career-high 15 points for the Sting (2-3).

The Sun led by nine at halftime and pulled away in the first
five minutes of the second half with a 12-4 run. Whalen had seven
points and a steal in the run that put the Sun up 46-29.
Connecticut led by 19 points down the stretch and the Sting got no
closer than 10 the rest of the way.

The Sun last played seven days ago, an 82-73 win over Los
Angeles, and the long time off showed early on.

"We were a little rusty for the six, seven minutes. Once we
scraped that off, we weren't too bad," Thibault said. "We just
had to make it that the shots they made had to be tough shots."

Charlotte took an early 7-0 lead on 3-of-3 shooting while
Connecticut missed its first four. The Sun chipped away and finally
caught the Sting with a 9-2 run midway through the first half.
Asjha Jones had five points in the run and Candace Futrell's layup
with 8:16 pulled Connecticut even at 18. Wendy Palmer's pull-up
jumper on the next possession gave the Sun the lead for good.

"They took our hit early and they were able to get a run
going," Sting guard Dawn Staley said. "They were really active
and we didn't respond quick enough."

Charlotte's Tammy Sutton-Brown had 12 points and two blocks
before going down with an ankle injury with 7 minutes to play. With
Sutton-Brown out of the game, Connecticut controlled the post the
rest of the way.

Palmer, Taj McWilliams Franklin and Katie Douglas each had seven
rebounds for Connecticut.

The Sun finished with 11 steals and had 21 assists on 25 field
goals. Douglas led Connecticut with seven assists. Douglas has 13
assists in the last two games and was coming off a 25-point
performance in the win over Los Angeles. She drew most of the
Sting's attention, allowing her teammates to find openings.

"I thought we did a good job on Katie, who was red hot coming
in, but we let players off the bench hurt us," Sting coach Trudi
Lacey said.
